    <title>OpenAI was a research lab — now it’s just another tech company</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="ISRAEL-SCIENCE-TECHNOLOGY-AI" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/DvB36uJg8KYBZ7pwEx2FRWNp-RI=/0x0:6000x4000/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73616251/1258459861.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Photo by Jack Guez / AFP via Getty Images&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="i1h4EY"&gt;Here’s the thing about asking investors for money: they want to see returns.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="rjjxJH"&gt;OpenAI launched with a famously altruistic mission: to help humanity by developing artificial general intelligence. But along the way, it became one of the best-funded companies in Silicon Valley. Now, the tension between those two facts is coming to a head. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="WlnQKy"&gt;Weeks after releasing a new model it claims can “reason,” OpenAI is barreling toward dropping its nonprofit status, some of its most senior employees are leaving, and CEO Sam Altman — who was once briefly ousted over apparent trust concerns — is solidifying his position as one of the most powerful people in tech.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="v5aeFN"&gt;On Wednesday, OpenAI’s longtime chief technology officer, Mira Murati, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/9/25/24254431/openai-cto-mira-murati-leaving"&gt;announced she’s leaving...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
